        ],
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_12",
        "observed_type": "image_body",
        "canon_role": "picture",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.20968769917144678,
          0.0760722527253919,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.33070740829155726
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_1",
        "observed_type": "title",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "BY ANDREA PETERSEN",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.07798201639213814,
          0.1159974506054812,
          0.08498448317020768
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "new study is helping to answer a pressing nutrition question: Which ultra-processed foods are harming our health—and which might not be so bad?",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.08975889233707329,
          0.19184193753983428,
          0.13527492639452535
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The problem is the way many packaged foods are made, re- searchers believe. Products such as many frozen pizzas, cereals and chips pack more calories per gram than less-processed foods do. And most ultra-processed foods have combinations of salt, fat, sugar and carbohydrates that aren't gen- erally found in nature, which can make us crave them. Diets high in packaged foods without those traits—such as canned peaches or refried beans—don't seem to lead people to overeat and gain weight, at least not as much.",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.13495663245006764,
          0.19375398342893563,
          0.2368106946765338
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Those are the findings so far of a continuing study investigating how ultra-processed food affects our bodies. Scientists presented their interim data at a workshop put on by the National Institutes of Health and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in December.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.2374472825654492,
          0.1950286806883365,
          0.28869260762314
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "\"There might be a way to create the quote, unquote healthy ultra- processed food that's still conve- nient,\" said Kevin D. Hall, the prin- cipal investigator of the study and a scientist at the NIH, giving an ex- ample of a frozen meal with brown rice, beans and a lot of vegetables.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.28741943184530916,
          0.19247928616953475,
          0.339619638736373
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_13",
        "observed_type": "title",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "Researchers Dig Into Risks Of Ultra-Processed Foods",
        "bbox": [
          0.2606755895474825,
          0.3380281690140845,
          0.9375398342893563,
          0.39341131534972545
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Ultra-processed foods make up about 58% of the calories that U.S. adults and children ages 1 and older consume in a day, according to an analysis of federal data. Foods are generally considered ul- tra-processed if they contain in- gredients that you wouldn't find in a home kitchen, such as high- fructose corn syrup and emulsifi- ers. Yet many scientists believe not all these foods are equally bad—and some might be reason- ably healthy.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.3386647569029999,
          0.1931166347992352,
          0.4277870613511578
        ],
        "order": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "How packaged products are made could hold answers to why some are more unhealthy",
        "bbox": [
          0.24155513065646908,
          0.39786743057213336,
          0.9496494582536648,
          0.4086894246836954
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_26",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.6042065009560229,
          0.42142118246200366,
          0.7826641172721479,
          0.472029919630779
        ],
        "order": 11
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_31",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The findings suggest that eat- ing packaged foods doesn't auto- matically result in overeating or weight gain, as long as you stick to foods such as canned refried beans or fruit cocktail, which are low in calories per gram and don't have the problematic combina- tions of fat. salt. carbs and sugar.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8005098789037604,
          0.42142118246200366,
          0.982791586998088,
          0.47807750457547543
        ],
        "order": 12
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "sodium, muffins are high in fat and sugar, and french fries are high in fat and sodium.",
        "bbox": [
          0.20905035054174634,
          0.42173947640646137,
          0.3760356915232632,
          0.44083711307392376
        ],
        "order": 13
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.4072657743785851,
          0.42173947640646137,
          0.5876354365838113,
          0.4659823346860826
        ],
        "order": 14
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Recent studies have linked diets high in ultra-processed foods to in- creased risks of obesity, Type 2 dia- betes, cancer, cardiovascular dis- ease and depression. Robert F. Kennedy Jr., the president-elect's nominee to lead the Department of Health and Human Services, blames chemicals and additives in food for widespread health problems.",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.4281053552956155,
          0.19375398342893563,
          0.49240073207607227
        ],
        "order": 15
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Researchers call these types of foods \"hyperpalatable\" and they have a strong effect on our brain's reward system, said Tera Fazzino, associate director of the Cofrin Lo- gan Center for Addiction Research and Treatment at the University of Kansas. This makes it difficult to",
        "bbox": [
          0.20968769917144678,
          0.44083711307392376,
          0.3919694072657744,
          0.49208243813161456
        ],
        "order": 16
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Plain nuts \"are good, they are pleasant to consume, but I don't eat the whole can in one sitting,\" Fazzino said.",
        "bbox": [
          0.40854047163798596,
          0.4663006286305403,
          0.5806246016571064,
          0.49176414418715686
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_28",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The diets contain roughly the same amounts of calories, fat, sugar, sodium and fiber.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6048438495857233,
          0.47298480146415217,
          0.7782026768642447,
          0.49176414418715686
        ],
        "order": 18
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_32",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "There are other concerns about convenience foods beyond weight gain. Some of the additives that many contain have been linked to health problems.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8024219247928617,
          0.47775921063101773,
          0.9834289356277884,
          0.5111800747990769
        ],
        "order": 19
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_27",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In interim results, which came from 18 people, participants re- ported feeling just as full and sat- isfied on all the diets. But when they were on the energy-dense diet with foods such as honey- roasted peanuts, they ate about 1,000 more calories a day than they did while eating the diet with plain oatmeal with strawber- ries and walnuts.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6042065009560229,
          0.49176414418715686,
          0.7845761631612492,
          0.5617888119678524
        ],
        "order": 20
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In the current NIH study, 36 par- ticipants live for a month at a fa- cility where their meals are tightly controlled. They spend each week on one of four diets. They are of- fered about 6,oo0 calories a day and can eat as much as they like. For one week, they eat mini- mally processed foods such as plain oatmeal with strawberries and walnuts. For the other weeks, they get versions of an ultra-pro- cessed diet.",
        "bbox": [
          0.40662842574888464,
          0.5041776080210074,
          0.5876354365838113,
          0.5872523275244689
        ],
        "order": 23
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "When companies make, say, an en. ergy bar, they often break down the cellular structure of the raw ingredients and remove the water, Hall said. Getting rid of water makes sense for food safety, Hall said, since moisture promotes the growth of bacteria.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.5054507837988382,
          0.19184193753983428,
          0.5554229330786982
        ],
        "order": 24
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_34",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The NIH research isn't complete. But its findings so far suggest you can choose healthier packaged foods by checking labels and cal- culating calories per gram. Avoid foods that clock in at two calories per gram or more, such as frozen meatballs, and stick to those that are around one calorie per gram, like low-fat flavored yogurt.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8017845761631612,
          0.5245484204663007,
          0.9815168897386871,
          0.5872523275244689
        ],
        "order": 27
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Preliminary study results and other research suggest that healthier choices for ultra-processed foods include (cid Canned peaches (c Canned refried beans (cid Canned fruit cocktail ci Jarred salsa i Low-sodium soups (cid Low-fat flavored yogurt stop eating them, Fazzino said. Many seemingly healthy foods are hyperpalatable, including many full-fat flavored yogurts (high fat, high sugar). Salted nuts are hyper- palatable (high sodium, high fat), but plain, unsalted nuts aren't.",
        "bbox": [
          0.22434671765455705,
          0.5363252964112358,
          0.372848948374761,
          0.5617888119678524
        ],
        "order": 28
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The process also makes foods more energy dense—meaning they contain more calories per gram than many minimally processed foods do. In the study, the meals with energy-dense foods had about two calories per gram, com- pared with about one calorie per gram for the meals with fewer en- ergy-dense foods.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.5557412270231559,
          0.1931166347992352,
          0.6190817219702395
        ],
        "order": 29
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_29",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Not all the ultra-processed di- ets had such dramatic calorie dif- ferences. When people were on the ultra-processed diet that was neither energy dense nor hyper- palatable, they consumed only about 170 calories more a day.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6042065009560229,
          0.5621071059123101,
          0.7807520713830465,
          0.6069865520808466
        ],
        "order": 30
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.22307202039515614,
          0.5678363969125487,
          0.36073932441045253,
          0.6394525344155327
        ],
        "order": 31
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_35",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Or you can combine foods to di- lute the overall energy density of your meal, Hall said. Instead of eat- ing chicken fingers with mac and cheese, have them with a big salad.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8017845761631612,
          0.5872523275244689,
          0.9840662842574889,
          0.6187634280257818
        ],
        "order": 32
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_24",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In one, the meals are energy dense—such as packaged oatmeal with added protein powder, sugar and cream and sweetened cranber ries—with most calories coming from hard-to-resist hyperpalatable foods, like honey-roasted peanuts.",
        "bbox": [
          0.4059910771191842,
          0.5875706214689266,
          0.5869980879541109,
          0.6321317736930054
        ],
        "order": 33
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_30",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "People gained about 1 pound after a week on the energy-dense and hard-to-resist diet. They lost about a half a pound on the mini- mally processed diet—and also on the one with the liquid-scrambled egg product.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6048438495857233,
          0.6060316702474735,
          0.7820267686424475,
          0.6515477043049256
        ],
        "order": 34
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_36",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "To avoid hyperpalatable foods, look for products that are low in sodium, Fazzino says. This can in- clude items such as low-sodium frozen meals and soups, she says.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8024219247928617,
          0.6181268401368664,
          0.9834289356277884,
          0.6512294103604679
        ],
        "order": 35
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In addition, many packaged foods combine fat, sugar, sodium and carbs in ways typically not found in nature. For instance, ba- gels are usually high in carbs and",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.6197183098591549,
          0.18865519439133205,
          0.6512294103604679
        ],
        "order": 36
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_25",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In a second ultra-processed diet, meals are energy dense, but fewer calories come from those hard-to-resist foods. The third diet included foods such as scram bled eggs from a liquid egg prod- uct with spinach, flavored yogurt and packaged oatmeal with fiber powder and heavy cream. Those meals weren't energy-dense or hard to resist.",
        "bbox": [
          0.40662842574888464,
          0.6318134797485477,
          0.5844486934353091,
          0.6509111164160102
        ],
        "order": 37
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_53",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "buy prints, but you can't share or download pho- tos until you make a pur- chase. Shutterfly-owned Snapfish has the same policy.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8540471637985978,
          0.6824222169173232,
          0.9808795411089866,
          0.7215723720856211
        ],
        "order": 39
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_52",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "一",
        "bbox": [
          0.4079031230082855,
          0.6833770987506963,
          0.840025493945188,
          0.8367947799793108
        ],
        "order": 40
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_54",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Flickr limits free ac- counts to 1,000 items and 50 nonpublic images. If you uploaded more than that back when Flickr was more widely used and had higher free-storage limits, the excess images are probably gone.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8540471637985978,
          0.7212540781411634,
          0.9859783301465902,
          0.7782286941990929
        ],
        "order": 41
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_38",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "BY SHARA TIBKEN",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.7333492480305562,
          0.09432759719566602,
          0.7403517148086257
        ],
        "order": 42
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_46",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "On a Mac, you can search by kind and select \"image\" or even specific image file types, including JPEG, TIFF, GIF, PNG, BMP and HEIC. (You can also search for \"movie\" files.) On Windows, you can search inside the taskbar, and can narrow down your query by specific file types.",
        "bbox": [
          0.20905035054174634,
          0.7336675419750139,
          0.3938814531548757,
          0.7849128670327047
        ],
        "order": 43
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_39",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Srts room for tasks that aren't so over- whelming.",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.7457627118644068,
          0.19184193753983428,
          0.7782286941990929
        ],
        "order": 44
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_40",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Who even knows where all those digital files are? There are tens of thousands of images in your iCloud. And more in your Google and Face- book accounts. And your dusty old hard drives. And even those old photo CDs you got from Walgreens a million years ago.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.7785469881435506,
          0.19247928616953475,
          0.829155725312326
        ],
        "order": 45
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_55",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "You probably have an old hard drive, flash drive or stack of CDs and DVDs somewhere with photos from your wedding, the birth of your first child or the birthday of a long- qone loved one.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8534098151688974,
          0.7957348611442667,
          0.9821542383683876,
          0.8476167740908729
        ],
        "order": 48
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_48",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If you use the Google Photos app on your phone or computer, it's easy to download the stored files using Google's Takeout tool.",
        "bbox": [
          0.2084130019120459,
          0.7979629187554707,
          0.39260675589547483,
          0.8224715524787141
        ],
        "order": 49
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_49",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "On your computer, open a Google webpage and click your picture in the top right corner. Choose \"Man- age Your Google Account,\" then se- lect \"Data & privacy.\" Choose \"Download your data,\" select what items you want to receive and how you want to receive them (such as a download link). You'll get a zip file you can then open and sift through. If you select Google Drive in the tool, you'll also download all other files you saved there. It might be too much. If you think you have images hiding in Google Drive, skip Takeout and just look around by fitering your search to \"Photos & images.\"",
        "bbox": [
          0.207138304652645,
          0.8234264343120872,
          0.39579349904397704,
          0.9316463754277075
        ],
        "order": 50
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_41",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "But you've got to start some- where, and now is the time. Plan to download photo files from wherever they might be stashed. Set up a system—such as a spreadsheet or sticky notes—to keep track of all the places you've checked, advises David Shor, co-founder of Tidy Haus, a home- and digital-organization com- nanv hased in Fort Worth. Texas.",
        "bbox": [
          0.011472275334608031,
          0.8294740192567837,
          0.1950286806883365,
          0.8915413384260364
        ],
        "order": 51
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_57",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "You can also find them in the Pho- tos app on your Mac, if you have iCloud photo sharing turned on.",
        "bbox": [
          0.40662842574888464,
          0.8479350680353306,
          0.5825366475462078,
          0.8676692925917084
        ],
        "order": 52
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_65",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Most laptops today don't have CD drives—or even the older USB-A ports. You might need to invest in a dongle adapter and an external CD/ DVD drive. Luckily, neither of those will break the bank.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8024219247928617,
          0.8488899498687037,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.8864486353147132
        ],
        "order": 54
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_62",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Photos isn't a download category of its own. You have to select Posts to get images, then choose the time frame and media quality you want to download.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6042065009560229,
          0.8740351714808626,
          0.7858508604206501,
          0.9055462719821755
        ],
        "order": 56
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_59",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Many of us have had Facebook ac- counts for over a decade and proba- bly shared photos from old cameras we no longer own.",
        "bbox": [
          0.4059910771191842,
          0.8804010503700167,
          0.5889101338432122,
          0.9055462719821755
        ],
        "order": 57
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_67",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In some cases, you might find a dead hard drive or even an old phone or tablet that you can't turn on but you suspect might contain some precious memories. If irre- placeable images are on the line, you may want to visit a tech repair shop.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8011472275334608,
          0.8870852232036286,
          0.9840662842574889,
          0.9319646693721652
        ],
        "order": 58
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_42",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "nt oave ite f project management in place so you don't mess up,\" he says.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.8912230444815787,
          0.1950286806883365,
          0.9119121508713297
        ],
        "order": 59
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_60",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Navigate to Meta's Accounts Center to download your photos. Choose \"Your information and per- missions\" from the left toolbar and then select \"Download your infor- mation.\" Choose which account you want to download (for instance, Facebook and/or Instagram), then decide how much data you want— everything available or specific types of information.",
        "bbox": [
          0.40662842574888464,
          0.9058645659266332,
          0.5844486934353091,
          0.9758892337073287
        ],
        "order": 60
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_43",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Here's a checklist for making sure you don't miss anything.",
        "bbox": [
          0.01338432122370937,
          0.9122304448157874,
          0.16762268961121735,
          0.924643908649638
        ],
        "order": 62
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_64",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Did you ever keep photos in Flickr, Shutterfly, Dropbox or a similar storage service? If you haven't logged in lately, those photos may be purged, so log in and check. In the case of Shutterfly, if you don't make a purchase every 18 months, your photos will be ar- chived. You can still see them and",
        "bbox": [
          0.6035691523263225,
          0.9192329115938569,
          0.7782026768642447,
          0.9758892337073287
        ],
        "order": 63
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_66",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Once you have all your digital photos in one place, backing them up to an external drive or catalog- ing them in your Photos app will be a lot easier. Then you can start wor- rying about all the photo prints you have stuffed in boxes in the attic.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8005098789037604,
          0.931009787538792,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.9758892337073287
        ],
        "order": 65
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_45",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Think all your photos are stored in that folder neatly labeled Pictures? Think again. Odds are high that im- ages are lurking in a Downloads folder or other random corners of your laptop.",
        "bbox": [
          0.009560229445506692,
          0.9383305482613193,
          0.1905672402804334,
          0.975570939762871
        ],
        "order": 67
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_009_51",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If you have an iPhone, you almost certainly have photos saved in iCloud. You can see and download them by going to iCloud.com/photos and signing in with your Apple ID.",
        "bbox": [
          0.2084130019120459,
          0.9450147210949311,
          0.39133205863607395,
          0.9758892337073287
        ],
        "order": 68
      }
    ]
  },
